(3. Key Design Decisions) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ Python backend: likely chosen because this project mixes API work, text parsing,) Tj
T*
(    and AI integration. Python is especially strong there.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ FastAPI over Flask or Django: FastAPI gives cleaner typing and validation than) Tj
T*
(    Flask, while staying lighter than Django. Good middle ground.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ React and Next.js frontend: strong ecosystem, reusable components, and industry) Tj
T*
(    relevance. It also teaches modern frontend patterns.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ SQLite over PostgreSQL or MySQL: fastest way to get persistence without running a) Tj
T*
(    separate database server.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ SQLAlchemy ORM: helpful because the app has structured relational data but still) Tj
T*
(    benefits from Python objects and query abstraction.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ Service-layer business logic: routes stay thin, while logic lives in services like) Tj
T*
(    backend/app/services/application_service.py. That is a good maintainability) Tj
T*
(    choice.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ Terminal-heavy workflow: common because it is scriptable, reproducible, fast, and) Tj
T*
(    works the same on local machines and servers.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(4. Alternative Implementations) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Backend alternatives) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ C#: you would likely use ASP.NET Core plus Entity Framework. Strong typing,) Tj
T*
(    excellent tooling, great for larger enterprise systems.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(‚ÄĘ Java: probably Spring Boot plus JPA or Hibernate. Very production-proven, but) Tj
T*
(    heavier and more verbose.) Tj
T*
() Tj
ET
